Yes, that's the right flow. Let me be precise about the split of responsibilities though, because SignServer only handles one part:
SignServer's job (raw crypto only): hold the private key and sign bytes you send it. It returns a raw signature. It does not know anything about DID documents, JCS, or Linked Data Proofs.
Your Django backend's job: everything else — canonicalization, constructing the proof, attaching it.
So the full flow is:
One-time SignServer setup:

Create a Soft CryptoToken (stores the key pair in DB)
Generate an Ed25519 key in that CryptoToken
Create a PlainSigner worker linked to the CryptoToken
Activate the worker

Per DID document signing (Django backend):

Build the DID document (without proof)
Canonicalize it with JCS (RFC 8785)
POST the canonicalized bytes to SignServer's /signserver/process HTTP API
Get back raw Ed25519 signature bytes
Construct the Data Integrity proof object (type, verificationMethod, proofValue, created, proofPurpose)
Attach proof to the DID document
Write the final did.json to the dids volume

